## v1.4.0 (2026-05-17)

**Changed by:** ProjectAgamemnon PR #398 partial-contamination recovery (Haiku bundle pair #398 + #401)
**Verification:** verified-ci

### What changed

- Added new subsection "Partial contamination variant (v1.4.0)" inside "Verified Workflow"
  documenting the case where ONE stray commit leaks from a sibling agent's branch (distinct
  from v1.3.0's full collapse of N branches onto one ref)
- Added recovery workflow: `git reset --hard origin/main && cherry-pick <own-shas> && push --force-with-lease`
- Added detection technique: `git log origin/<branch> ^origin/main --oneline` → N+1 commits
- Added 1 new Failed Attempts row covering the PR #398/#401 contamination
- Added 1 new Verified On row for ProjectAgamemnon PR #398 (2026-05-17)
- Extended frontmatter `description` with trigger (10) describing the partial-contamination
  detection signal
- Documented two failed recovery approaches (`git revert <stray>` and `git rebase --onto`)
  and why reset+cherry-pick is preferred
- Added prevention rules: forbid `git pull` inside agent worktrees, validate diff scope
  against expected-files list before push
- Bumped version to 1.4.0 (minor — new section + new failure mode, no breaking changes)

### Why

v1.3.0 covered the visible failure (4 branches collapse onto 1 ref under 1 PR). The
partial-contamination variant is more dangerous because each PR still appears to be its own
branch — the bug is only visible when someone reads the diff and notices out-of-scope files.
Detected on ProjectAgamemnon PR #398: agent's diff contained an unrelated `nats_client.cpp`
change that originated from PR #401's branch. Recovery via `git reset --hard origin/main`
+ cherry-pick of own commits + `push --force-with-lease` rebuilt a clean branch; CI re-ran
green and the PR auto-squash merged. Documenting this as a separate variant so future
sessions can distinguish "wrong PR has my commit" (v1.4.0) from "all commits collapsed to
one PR" (v1.3.0) and apply the correct recovery.

